# Generating grouped data
x, y = datasets.make_blobs(n_samples=1000, centers=2, random_state=0, cluster_std=0.5)
# Splitting the training and testing data
half = int(len(x) / 2)
train_x = x[:half]
test_x = x[half:]
train_y = y[:half]
test_y = y[half:]
# Creating a scatter plot to look at all of the the initial data
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
scatter = ax.scatter(x[:, 0], x[:, 1], c = y, cmap = 'tab20c')
ax.set(xlabel='Input 1', ylabel='Input 2', title = 'Scatter Plot of Generated Data')
ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), loc="lower left", title="Classes", bbox_to_anchor=(1, .63));

First I am going to explain the tensorflow model below and some of the parameters used.

The model below is sequential. This just means that the data flows through the model sequentially, meaning one layer at a time in the order they are listed below. The first layer is using a rectifier (relu) activation function while the second has a sigmoid activation function. Below is the mathematical expression for those two functions.

Relu: $f(x) = max(0,x)$

Sigmoid: $f(x) = \frac{e^x}{e^x + 1}$

Now for the parameters included when compiling the model. First we have the loss, this is used to determine the error between the predicted outputs and the actual outputs. For this I choose the cross-entropy loss function. Next is the optimizer, this is something that is used to try and minimize the loss. In this case, the algorithm I chose was adam. It optimized the learning rate to better the weight predictions. Lastly we have the metrics, this is similar to the loss function, however it is not used when training the model. I picked the accuracy metric, which will tell us how often the correct classification was predicted. Two remaining things to explain are the parameters in fitting the model. Those two are below.

Epoch - When an entire dataset has passed through the neural network once.

batch_size - Total number of training examples present in a single batch.

In [3]:
init_weights = []
final_weights = []
pred = []
acc = []
for i in range(1,6):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential()
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(50, input_dim=2, activation='relu', name='L1'))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid', name='Output'))
    # Initial weights
    init_weights.append(model.get_weights())
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001), metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.fit(tf.convert_to_tensor(train_x), tf.convert_to_tensor(train_y), epochs=10, batch_size=10, verbose=0);
    # Final weights
    final_weights.append(model.get_weights())
    pred.append(model.predict(tf.convert_to_tensor(test_x)))
    acc.append(model.evaluate(tf.convert_to_tensor(test_x), tf.convert_to_tensor(test_y)))
pred = np.around(pred)

# Creating a scatter plot to look at all of the the initial data
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
scatter = ax.scatter(x[:, 0], x[:, 1], color = '#505DAB')
ax.set(xlabel='Input 1', ylabel='Input 2', title = 'Scatter Plot of Generated Data');
In [6]:
sil = []
sse = []
for i in range(2,7):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=0).fit(x)
    #print(len(kmeans.labels_))
    kmeans_cluster_centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    kmeans_labels = pairwise_distances_argmin(x, kmeans_cluster_centers)
    sil.append(silhouette_score(x, kmeans.labels_, metric = 'euclidean'))
    pred_clusters = kmeans.predict(x)
    curr_sse = 0
    # calculate square of Euclidean distance of each point from its cluster center and add to current WSS
    for j in range(len(x)):
        curr_center = kmeans_cluster_centers[pred_clusters[j]]
        curr_sse += (x[j, 0] - curr_center[0]) ** 2 + (x[j, 1] - curr_center[1]) ** 2
      
    sse.append(curr_sse)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    colors = ['#06F979', '#FF9C34', '#060DF9', '#F90687', '#523B0A', '#f9f206']
    for k, col in zip(range(i), colors):
        my_members = kmeans_labels == k
        cluster_center = kmeans_cluster_centers[k]
        ax.plot(x[my_members, 0], x[my_members, 1], 'w',
            markerfacecolor=col, marker='.')
        ax.plot(cluster_center[0], cluster_center[1], 'o', markerfacecolor=col,
            markeredgecolor='k', markersize=6)
    ax.set(xlabel='Input 1', ylabel='Input 2', title = 'K-Means with ' + str(i) + ' clusters');

Above we can see the data grouped into clusters ranging from 2 to 6. Now let's try and see which value of k is the optimal. To do this we will look at two different plots. The first will be an elbow plot. This shows the number of clusters vs the sum of squared errors. Where the plot starts to converge is the elbow and optimal number of clusters. Next we will look at the silhouette score. This measures how similar a point is within its own cluster when compared to other clusters. The euclidean distance is used at the metric for the silhouette score.

In [7]:
plt.plot(np.arange(2, len(sse)+2), sse)
plt.title('Elbow Plot')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Errors');
In [8]:
plt.plot(np.arange(2, len(sil)+2), sil)
plt.title('Silhouette Score')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Score');

The two plots above show that the optimal number of clusters for this data is 4. It is where the elbow plot converges and the silhouette score peaks. It is important to use the optimal k value when forming clusters because it minimizes the error. When the error is minimized more confidence can be placed in the classified or grouped values.
